	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>A comprehensive EPA in sight?</h1>

			
			<h4>
												06 September 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to the EU Delegate to Namibia, quoted in press reports, ‘the EU endorsed the request by countries of the Southern African Development Community (SADC) to conclude a full EPA agreement by year-end’, following a further round of negotiations at both technical and Ministerial level. EU Head of Delegation Elisabeth Pape added that ‘there will be three more such meetings in due course before the signing’, leading to the conclusion of ‘a full agreement and not an interim EPA’.</p><p>As the June 2010 EC overview of the state of EPA negotiations observed, concluding the IEPAs has ‘taken much longer than anticipated’. The overview notes that following requests from ACP governments, ‘the EU revised certain provisions already contained in the IEPAs … in order to include revisions in the comprehensive regional EPA.’ However this saw an increase in requests for renegotiations, as ‘issues specific to an area in one negotiation were often taken up by a neighbouring configuration.’ As a consequence, as the EC note acknowledged, ‘as negotiations advanced and issues were addressed and mostly resolved, it became increasingly difficult for countries and regions to sign the IEPAs previously initialled, since they do not include these new provisions.’ However this gave rise to an impasse, since the advanced provisional application of the market access provisions of the IEPAs granting full duty-free, quota-free access through regulation 1528/2007 was ‘predicated upon the IEPA that [had been] initialled being signed and applied’. It now appears, from comments by the EU Delegate reported in <i>the Namibian</i> newspaper on 30 July 2010, that a way out of the impasse has been found.</p><p>Meanwhile, South African Deputy Director-General of Trade and Industry Xavier Carim is quoted as stating that ‘it would be possible to finalise the agreement by year-end’, but that this would ‘require flexibility from the EC to open up its markets in certain sectors’, with South Africa reciprocating to a degree. According to academic commentary from the University of Pretoria, ‘South Africa is particularly interested in increased access for certain agricultural goods, where high tariffs and strict sanitary and phytosanitary rules hamper trade.’ Currently ‘European agricultural exporters have easier access to South Africa than vice versa.’</p><p>According to press reports, the likelihood of a comprehensive EPA agreement being concluded appears to have been enhanced by the EU granting ‘a five-year extension for agreement on next-generation issues, including services and investment, which will allow states time to strengthen their regulatory frameworks before opening up their markets.’</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>The Namibian</i>, ‘Last obstacles for EPA signing removed’, 30 July 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://www.thedailyafrican.com/namibia/76929-Last-Obstacles-for-EPA-Signing-Removed.html" target="_self">http://www.thedailyafrican.com/namibia/76929-Last-Obstacles-for-EPA-Sign...</a></p><p><i>timeslive.co.za</i>, ‘New hope for conclusion of trade negotiations between Southern Africa and EC’, 18 July 2010 </p><p>
<a href="http://www.timeslive.co.za/business/article555622.ece/New-hope-for-conclusion-of-trade-negotiations-with-EC" target="_self">http://www.timeslive.co.za/business/article555622.ece/New-hope-for-concl...</a></p><p>TRALAC, commentary, ‘Recent developments in the SADC EPA negotiations’, 11 August 2010 </p><p>
<a href="http://www.tralac.org/cgi-bin/giga.cgi?cmd=cause_dir_news_item&amp;cause_id=1694&amp;news_id=91081&amp;cat_id=1059" target="_self">http://www.tralac.org/cgi-bin/giga.cgi?cmd=cause_dir_news_item&amp;cause...</a></p><p><i>Mmegi Online</i>, ‘More time needed for EPA talks – Motlhale’, 9 August 2010 </p><p>
<a href="http://www.tralac.org/cgi-bin/giga.cgi?cmd=cause_dir_news_item&amp;cause_id=1694&amp;news_id=91014&amp;cat_id=1026" target="_self">http://www.tralac.org/cgi-bin/giga.cgi?cmd=cause_dir_news_item&amp;cause...</a></p><p>EC, ‘ACP-EU EPAs: State of play at June 2010’, Ref. TRADE D2 D(2010), 15 June 2010 </p><p>
<a href="http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/docs/2010/june/tradoc_146263.pdf" target="_self">http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/docs/2010/june/tradoc_146263.pdf</a> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The July round of negotiations at technical and senior official level saw progress made in resolving contentious issues, although there remains a range of issues to be addressed if a comprehensive EPA is to be concluded by the end of the year. It appears that the conclusion of a comprehensive EPA will lead to Namibian concerns over the continued right to use a range of agricultural trade policy tools being satisfactorily addressed. However, issues of systemic interest to the EC relating to geographical indicators, intellectual property rights protection, sustainable development, labour standards, government procurement and competition policy, will all still need to be addressed. The economic implications of the various specific provisions to be included in these areas will also need to be fully assessed before agreement is reached.</p><p>Moving towards the harmonisation of treatment accorded to SADC EPA members, in terms of access for agricultural products to the EU market, is likely to prove difficult, given the high level of ambition when it comes to improved market access for food and agricultural exports. A particular area of controversy is likely to be the treatment of South African sugar exports: with the recently concluded FTAs with Central American and Andean Pact countries including TRQs for sugar exports, the South African Sugar Association is pushing strongly for similar TRQs in a comprehensive SADC-EU EPA. A number of Botswana, Lesotho, Namibia and Swaziland (BLNS) industries and governments are concerned about the impact of expanded duty-free access for South African agricultural exports on both their market position and future investment flows. </p><p>These concerns will need to be pragmatically addressed by both EU and South African negotiators in the affected sectors. </p>
		</div>
		
